## Cain and Abel (27-32)

The first murder in human history. The Quran doesn't name them (they're called "the two sons of Adam"), but Islamic tradition identifies them as **Qabil** (Cain) and **Habil** (Abel).

Both offer a sacrifice to God. One is accepted, the other isn't. The rejected brother is consumed by jealousy:

*"I will surely kill you."*

His brother's response is remarkable:

> *"If you stretch your hand toward me to kill me, I shall not stretch my hand toward you to kill you. I fear God, Lord of the worlds."* (28)

He won't fight back. Not because he's weak, but because he refuses to become a killer. He'd rather be the victim than the aggressor.

Cain kills him anyway. Then he's lost. He doesn't even know what to do with the body. God sends a **crow** that scratches at the ground, burying something in the earth. Cain watches and realizes: *that's* how you bury the dead.

> *"He said: Woe to me! Am I unable to be even like this crow and bury the body of my brother? And he became of those who regret."* (31)

The first murderer is taught burial by a bird. There's something deeply humbling about that.

---

Then comes one of the most quoted verses in the Quran:

> *"Whoever kills a soul, unless for a soul or for corruption in the land, it is as if he had slain all of mankind. And whoever saves one, it is as if he had saved all of mankind."* (32)

**"Unless for a soul"** means: except as legal punishment for murder (a life for a life). **"Or for corruption in the land"** means: except for those who wage war and spread destruction.

Outside of those two cases, taking *one* life is equivalent to killing *all of humanity*. And saving *one* life is equivalent to saving everyone. That's the weight the Quran places on a single person's existence.

