## Each Community Has Its Own Law (44-48)

The surah confirms the **Torah**:

> *"Indeed, We sent down the Torah, in which was guidance and light."* (44)

And the **Gospel**:

> *"And We sent, following in their footsteps, Jesus, the son of Mary, confirming what came before him in the Torah; and We gave him the Gospel, in which was guidance and light."* (46)

Then Muhammad is told to judge by the Quran. Each prophet received laws suited to their time and people.

Then a remarkable verse:

> *"For each of you We have made a law and a method. Had God willed, He would have made you one community, but He tests you in what He has given you. So compete in doing good."* (48)

God *deliberately* made different communities with different laws. This isn't an error or a temporary arrangement. The diversity is **intentional**. Jews have the Torah, Christians have the Gospel, Muslims have the Quran. The only competition that matters: **who does the most good**.

This is one of the Quran's most pluralistic verses. It doesn't say everyone else is wrong. It says everyone was given their own path, and the real test is what you do with it.
